1038
01:06:14,000 --> 01:06:17,000
well, what constitutes human flourishing and what sorts

1039
01:06:17,000 --> 01:06:22,000
of healthy societies will facilitate human flourishing?

1040
01:06:22,000 --> 01:06:25,000
And it seems to me, there are lots of them in the world today

1041
01:06:25,000 --> 01:06:29,000
that are not very healthy, but Americans love to criticize themselves.

1042
01:06:29,000 --> 01:06:32,000
I think we're pretty well off compared with, let's say,

1043
01:06:32,000 --> 01:06:34,000
what's happening in Syria.

1044
01:06:34,000 --> 01:06:36,000
I'm sure there are lots of joys to be had in Syria,

1045
01:06:36,000 --> 01:06:40,000
but right now I'd rather be in Indiana and a whole lot

1046
01:06:40,000 --> 01:06:42,000
of other areas of the world that that's true.

1047
01:06:42,000 --> 01:06:44,000
So I don't have an answer to your question,

1048
01:06:44,000 --> 01:06:48,000
but what I provide, I hope, is a framework for ontology

1049
01:06:48,000 --> 01:06:51,000
for posing the questions.

1050
01:06:51,000 --> 01:06:53,000
Okay, you're on.

1051
01:06:53,000 --> 01:06:56,000
Okay, this one's a doozy, all right.

1052
01:06:56,000 --> 01:06:59,000
And it's been bothering me for a while.

1053
01:06:59,000 --> 01:07:03,000
What the hell is an institution and what the hell is a society?

1054
01:07:03,000 --> 01:07:05,000
I mean, the institution is more important

1055
01:07:05,000 --> 01:07:07,000
because you've been using the word a lot.

1056
01:07:07,000 --> 01:07:09,000
An institution, what is that?

1057
01:07:09,000 --> 01:07:13,000
Yeah, as I've told you, an institution is a system of constitutive rules.

1058
01:07:13,000 --> 01:07:15,000
Within those systems of constitutive rules,

1059
01:07:15,000 --> 01:07:18,000
you create institutional facts.

1060
01:07:18,000 --> 01:07:21,000
All institutional facts are created by the application

1061
01:07:21,000 --> 01:07:25,000
of a same type of speech act or the same type of linguistic representation,

1062
01:07:25,000 --> 01:07:28,000
a status function declaration.

1063
01:07:28,000 --> 01:07:30,000
Now, there are immediate objections to that

1064
01:07:30,000 --> 01:07:33,000
because some of the things we think of as institutions

1065
01:07:33,000 --> 01:07:37,000
are not institutional facts on my account.

1066
01:07:37,000 --> 01:07:40,000
So the Christian calendar is not an institution

1067
01:07:40,000 --> 01:07:45,000
because being such and such a date doesn't carry a deontology.

1068
01:07:45,000 --> 01:07:48,000
The test is, does it carry a deontology?

1069
01:07:48,000 --> 01:07:50,000
Christmas Day is an institutional fact

1070
01:07:50,000 --> 01:07:55,000
because I have obligations and rights on Christmas Day.

1071
01:07:55,000 --> 01:07:58,000
I am obligated to give my children presents

1072
01:07:58,000 --> 01:08:00,000
and I have a right to a day off.

1073
01:08:00,000 --> 01:08:03,000
It marks it as an institutional fact.

1074
01:08:03,000 --> 01:08:05,000
That's a status function.

1075
01:08:05,000 --> 01:08:07,000
So there are tests for status functions.

1076
01:08:07,000 --> 01:08:09,000
Does it carry a deontology?

1077
01:08:09,000 --> 01:08:13,000
But the short answer is institutions are systems of constitutive rules.

1078
01:08:13,000 --> 01:08:16,000
They enable the creation of institutional facts

1079
01:08:16,000 --> 01:08:18,000
by status function declarations.

1080
01:08:18,000 --> 01:08:23,000
Status function declarations without exception create deontic powers

1081
01:08:23,000 --> 01:08:27,000
and deontic powers are the glue that holds human civilization together

1082
01:08:27,000 --> 01:08:29,000
because they give us reason for acting

1083
01:08:29,000 --> 01:08:33,000
that are independent of our immediate inclinations.

1084
01:08:33,000 --> 01:08:36,000
That's a summary of the lecture.

1085
01:08:40,000 --> 01:08:43,000
You brought this up towards the end concerning conflict

1086
01:08:43,000 --> 01:08:48,000
and the degree to which declarations must be accepted on mass

1087
01:08:48,000 --> 01:08:50,000
for them to have causative effect.

1088
01:08:50,000 --> 01:08:53,000
But then it seems that this propositional logical structure

1089
01:08:53,000 --> 01:08:56,000
doesn't have very much prescriptive power.

1090
01:08:56,000 --> 01:08:59,000
Most of the things you can prove from this logical structure

1091
01:08:59,000 --> 01:09:01,000
are actually descriptive.

1092
01:09:01,000 --> 01:09:06,000
I look at my set of axioms which are the result of having already fought wars

1093
01:09:06,000 --> 01:09:09,000
and then I draw the facts from there.

1094
01:09:09,000 --> 01:09:14,000
So my predecessor on this side asked for could you avert society

1095
01:09:14,000 --> 01:09:19,000
simply by describing society as an iterative process of declarations.

1096
01:09:19,000 --> 01:09:21,000
But I have a more basic question.

1097
01:09:21,000 --> 01:09:27,000
Does this actually give you any prescriptive, proof-based power at all

1098
01:09:27,000 --> 01:09:31,000
or do you throw it out there and then see who wins might make right style?

1099
01:09:31,000 --> 01:09:32,000
Yeah.

1100
01:09:32,000 --> 01:09:36,000
Well, okay, that's a larger question than I'll really be able to answer

1101
01:09:36,000 --> 01:09:39,000
but I would say there are lots of institutions

1102
01:09:39,000 --> 01:09:43,000
that are so obviously useful to all of us

1103
01:09:43,000 --> 01:09:47,000
that they really are not subject to challenge as institutions.

1104
01:09:47,000 --> 01:09:49,000
Most obvious is language.

1105
01:09:49,000 --> 01:09:52,000
If you think that private property is a bad idea,

1106
01:09:52,000 --> 01:09:55,000
okay, you can argue against private property.

1107
01:09:55,000 --> 01:09:57,000
But how would you argue against language?

1108
01:09:57,000 --> 01:10:00,000
You'd have to use language to argue against language

1109
01:10:00,000 --> 01:10:04,000
and I don't, I mean it's just pretty hard to see language being challenged

1110
01:10:04,000 --> 01:10:05,000
as an institution.

1111
01:10:05,000 --> 01:10:08,000
Now some institutions are inherently evil.

1112
01:10:08,000 --> 01:10:12,000
Slavery seems to me, a slavery of human being seems to me inherently evil.

1113
01:10:12,000 --> 01:10:16,000
But then that's something you can argue for.

1114
01:10:16,000 --> 01:10:19,000
That's something you can, within institutional structures,

1115
01:10:19,000 --> 01:10:20,000
you can make that out.

1116
01:10:20,000 --> 01:10:26,000
There are some, as I said, institutions that are so obviously beneficial to everybody

1117
01:10:26,000 --> 01:10:30,000
that it's very hard to see how anybody could argue against them

1118
01:10:30,000 --> 01:10:32,000
and language is the most obvious case.

1119
01:10:32,000 --> 01:10:33,000
But there are others.

1120
01:10:33,000 --> 01:10:34,000
How about money?

1121
01:10:34,000 --> 01:10:36,000
Money is an institution.

1122
01:10:36,000 --> 01:10:37,000
Is it beneficial?

1123
01:10:37,000 --> 01:10:39,000
I think on balance it is.

1124
01:10:39,000 --> 01:10:41,000
It's famously the root of all evil,

1125
01:10:41,000 --> 01:10:43,000
but it's the root of an awful lot of good too.

1126
01:10:43,000 --> 01:10:46,000
I try to imagine what your life would be like

1127
01:10:46,000 --> 01:10:50,000
if you had no possibility of buying and selling or being paid

1128
01:10:50,000 --> 01:10:53,000
or being paid for your work or anything like that.

1129
01:10:53,000 --> 01:10:57,000
It's very hard to imagine how you would organize a decent life.

1130
01:10:57,000 --> 01:11:00,000
So there are lots of institutions that are very pervasive

1131
01:11:00,000 --> 01:11:04,000
that are effectively harmless.

1132
01:11:04,000 --> 01:11:06,000
Now how about private property?

1133
01:11:06,000 --> 01:11:11,000
Well I think private property, again, benefits just about everybody.

1134
01:11:11,000 --> 01:11:15,000
But we now have in the United States such a disproportionate

1135
01:11:15,000 --> 01:11:19,000
concentration of private property, the famous 1%.

1136
01:11:19,000 --> 01:11:22,000
The wealth is so disproportionately concentrated

1137
01:11:22,000 --> 01:11:25,000
that it seems to me very unhealthy.

1138
01:11:25,000 --> 01:11:28,000
It's just not a healthy way to run a society

1139
01:11:28,000 --> 01:11:31,000
to have so much power, so much deontic power

1140
01:11:31,000 --> 01:11:34,000
in the hands of so few people.

1141
01:11:34,000 --> 01:11:37,000
For one thing, it gives them a disproportionate amount of political power.

1142
01:11:37,000 --> 01:11:41,000
And these are real problems that we're going to have to face.

1143
01:11:41,000 --> 01:11:44,000
So I think if you want to ask about a given institution,

1144
01:11:44,000 --> 01:11:46,000
is this institution a good one or a bad one,

1145
01:11:46,000 --> 01:11:49,000
you have to tell me more about the institution

1146
01:11:49,000 --> 01:11:52,000
and what it does, how it functions in human life.

1147
01:11:52,000 --> 01:11:54,000
Yeah.

